  "prompt": "Can an isosceles triangle be a right triangle? Why or why not?",
  "response": "Yes, an isosceles triangle can be a right triangle. An isosceles triangle is defined as a triangle with at least two sides of equal length. A right triangle has one angle of 90 degrees, forming a right angle.\n\nCombining these definitions, an isosceles right triangle would have two equal sides and one angle of 90 degrees. This configuration is possible. In fact, in the isosceles right triangle, the two equal sides are the legs, and the hypotenuse is the side opposite the right angle.\n\nFor instance, if the two legs are both of length \\(a\\), the hypotenuse will be \\(a\\sqrt{2}\\) by the Pythagorean theorem. This configuration maintains both the properties of being isosceles (two sides of equal length) and a right triangle (one angle of 90 degrees).",
